  "content:encoded": "<p>Last November, I attended the beautiful conference <a href=\"https://conferences.cirm-math.fr/2077.html\">Prime Numbers, Determinism and Pseudorandomness</a> at <a href=\"https://www.cirm-math.com/\">CIRM</a>. This conference was originally prepared to celebrate the 60th birthday of <a href=\"https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christian_Mauduit_(mathématicien)\">Christian Mauduit</a>, but unfortunately a tragic event during the summer of 2019 made that this conference ended up becoming a celebration of the memory of Christian.</p>\n<p>The links to the titles, abstracts, slides and videos for the talks of this excellent meeting can be found <a href=\"https://www.cirm-math.fr/Schedule/screen_display.php?id_renc=2077\">here</a>.</p>\n<p>In this blog post, I would like to transcript my notes for the amazing survey talk &#8220;<a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HSyG1ywF8So\">On ellipsephic integers</a>&#8221; by <a href=\"http://www.iecl.univ-lorraine.fr/~Cecile.Dartyge/\">Cécile Dartyge</a> on one of Christian&#8217;s favorite topics in Analytic Number Theory, namely, the statistics of integers missing some digits.</p>\n<p>Of course, all mistakes in the sequel are my sole responsibility.</p>\n<p><b>1. Introduction</b></p>\n<p><em>Ellipsephic integers</em> refers to a collection of integers with missing digits in a certain basis (e.g., all integers whose representation in basis 10 doesn&#8217;t contain the digit 9). Christian Mauduit proposed this nomenclature partly because <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ellipsis_(linguistics)\">ellipsis</a> = missing and psiphic = digit in Greek.</p>\n<p>Formally, we consider a basis <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Br%5Cin%5Cmathbb%7BN%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{r&#92;in&#92;mathbb{N}}\" class=\"latex\" />, <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Br%5Cgeq+3%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{r&#92;geq 3}\" class=\"latex\" />, and a subset <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;mathcal{D}}\" class=\"latex\" /> of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7B0%2C+1%2C+%5Cdots%2C+r-1%5C%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;{0, 1, &#92;dots, r-1&#92;}}\" class=\"latex\" /> of cardinality <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2%5Cleq%5C%23%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%5Cleq+r-1%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{2&#92;leq&#92;#&#92;mathcal{D}&#92;leq r-1}\" class=\"latex\" />. The corresponding set of ellipsephic integers <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BW_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{W_{&#92;mathcal{D}}}\" class=\"latex\" /> is</p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+W_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%3A%3D%5Cleft%5C%7Bn%3D%5Csum%5Climits_%7Bj%3D0%7D%5Ek+a_j+r%5Ej%3A+a_j%5Cin%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D+%5C%2C+%5C%2C+%5C%2C%5Cforall%5C%2C1%5Cleq+j%5Cleq+k%5Cright%5C%7D.&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle W_{&#92;mathcal{D}}:=&#92;left&#92;{n=&#92;sum&#92;limits_{j=0}^k a_j r^j: a_j&#92;in&#92;mathcal{D} &#92;, &#92;, &#92;,&#92;forall&#92;,1&#92;leq j&#92;leq k&#92;right&#92;}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p>\n<p>The subset of ellipsephic integers below a certain threshold <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{x}\" class=\"latex\" /> is denoted by</p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+W_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%28x%29%3A%3D%5C%7Bn%5Cin+W_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%3A+n%3C+x%5C%7D.&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle W_{&#92;mathcal{D}}(x):=&#92;{n&#92;in W_{&#92;mathcal{D}}: n< x&#92;}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p>\n<p>For the sake of exposition, we shall assume from now on that <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B0%5Cin%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{0&#92;in&#92;mathcal{D}}\" class=\"latex\" /> and</p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+gcd%28d%5Cin%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%29%3D1&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle gcd(d&#92;in&#92;mathcal{D})=1\" class=\"latex\" /></p>\n<p>unless it is explicitly said otherwise.</p>\n<p><b>2. Ellipsephic integers on arithmetic progressions</b></p>\n<p>Let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BW_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%28x%2Ca%2Cq%29+%3A%3D+%5C%7Bn%5Cin+W_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%28x%29%3A+n%5Cequiv+a+%5C%2C+%28%5Ctextrm%7Bmod+%7D+q%29%5C%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{W_{&#92;mathcal{D}}(x,a,q) := &#92;{n&#92;in W_{&#92;mathcal{D}}(x): n&#92;equiv a &#92;, (&#92;textrm{mod } q)&#92;}}\" class=\"latex\" />. Despite their sparseness, it was proved by <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=1625049\">Erdös, Mauduit and Sárközy</a> that ellipsephic integers behave well (i.e., &#8220;à la <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siegel--Walfisz_theorem\">Siegel-Walfisz</a>&#8221;) along arithmetic progressions:</p>\n<blockquote><p><b>Theorem 1 (Erdös&#8211;Mauduit&#8211;Sárközy)</b> <em>There are two constants <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bc_1%3Dc_1%28r%2C%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%29%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{c_1=c_1(r,&#92;mathcal{D})}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bc_2%3Dc_2%28r%2C%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%29%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{c_2=c_2(r,&#92;mathcal{D})}\" class=\"latex\" /> such that</em></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+%5Cleft%7C%5C%23W_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%28x%2Ca%2Cq%29-%5Cfrac%7B%5C%23W_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%28x%29%7D%7Bq%7D%5Cright%7C%5Cll_%7Br%2C%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%5Cfrac%7B%5C%23W_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%28x%29%7D%7Bq%7D%5Cexp%5Cleft%28-c_2%5Cfrac%7B%5Clog+x%7D%7B%5Clog+q%7D%5Cright%29&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle &#92;left|&#92;#W_{&#92;mathcal{D}}(x,a,q)-&#92;frac{&#92;#W_{&#92;mathcal{D}}(x)}{q}&#92;right|&#92;ll_{r,&#92;mathcal{D}}&#92;frac{&#92;#W_{&#92;mathcal{D}}(x)}{q}&#92;exp&#92;left(-c_2&#92;frac{&#92;log x}{&#92;log q}&#92;right)\" class=\"latex\" /></p>\n<p><em>for all <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%5Cin%5Cmathbb%7BN%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{a&#92;in&#92;mathbb{N}}\" class=\"latex\" />, <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bgcd%28q%2Cr%28r-1%29%29%3D1%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{gcd(q,r(r-1))=1}\" class=\"latex\" />, <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bq%5Cleq+%5Cexp%28c_1%5Csqrt%7B%5Clog+x%7D%29%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{q&#92;leq &#92;exp(c_1&#92;sqrt{&#92;log x})}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{x}\" class=\"latex\" /> sufficiently large.</em></p></blockquote>\n<p><em>Proof:</em> As it is usual in this kind of counting problem, one relies on <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponential_sum\">exponential sums</a>. More precisely, note that</p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+%5C%23W_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%28x%2Ca%2Cq%29+%3D+%5Cfrac%7B1%7D%7Bq%7D%5Csum%5Climits_%7Bh%3D1%7D%5Eq%5Csum%5Climits_%7Bn%5Cin+W_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%28x%29%7D+e%5Cleft%28%5Cfrac%7Bh%28n-a%29%7D%7Bq%7D%5Cright%29&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle &#92;#W_{&#92;mathcal{D}}(x,a,q) = &#92;frac{1}{q}&#92;sum&#92;limits_{h=1}^q&#92;sum&#92;limits_{n&#92;in W_{&#92;mathcal{D}}(x)} e&#92;left(&#92;frac{h(n-a)}{q}&#92;right)\" class=\"latex\" /></p>\n<p>where <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Be%28t%29%3A%3D%5Cexp%282%5Cpi+i+t%29%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{e(t):=&#92;exp(2&#92;pi i t)}\" class=\"latex\" />. The &#8220;main term&#8221; <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%23W_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%28x%29%2Fq%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;#W_{&#92;mathcal{D}}(x)/q}\" class=\"latex\" /> comes from the case <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bh%3Dq%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{h=q}\" class=\"latex\" />, so that our task consists into estimating the &#8220;error term&#8221;. For this sake, one has essentially to study</p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+F_%7BN%2C%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%28h%2Fq%29%3A%3D%5Csum%5Climits_%7Bn%5Cin+W_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%28x%29%7D+e%5Cleft%28%5Cfrac%7Bhn%7D%7Bq%7D%5Cright%29&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle F_{N,&#92;mathcal{D}}(h/q):=&#92;sum&#92;limits_{n&#92;in W_{&#92;mathcal{D}}(x)} e&#92;left(&#92;frac{hn}{q}&#92;right)\" class=\"latex\" /></p>\n<p>where <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%3A%3Dr%5EN%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{x:=r^N}\" class=\"latex\" />. Observe that</p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+F_%7BN%2C%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%28h%2Fq%29%3D%5Cprod%5Climits_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5E%7BN-1%7D%5Cleft%28%5Csum%5Climits_%7Bd%5Cin%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7De%5Cleft%28%5Cfrac%7Bhdr%5Ej%7D%7Bq%7D%5Cright%29%5Cright%29%3A%3D%5Cprod%5Climits_%7Bj%3D1%7D%5E%7BN-1%7D+u_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%28hr%5Ej%2Fq%29.&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle F_{N,&#92;mathcal{D}}(h/q)=&#92;prod&#92;limits_{j=1}^{N-1}&#92;left(&#92;sum&#92;limits_{d&#92;in&#92;mathcal{D}}e&#92;left(&#92;frac{hdr^j}{q}&#92;right)&#92;right):=&#92;prod&#92;limits_{j=1}^{N-1} u_{&#92;mathcal{D}}(hr^j/q).\" class=\"latex\" /></p>\n<p>The terms <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bu_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%28hr%5Ej%2Fq%29%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{u_{&#92;mathcal{D}}(hr^j/q)}\" class=\"latex\" /> are controlled thanks to the following lemma (giving some saving over the trivial bound <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%7Cu_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%28%5Calpha%29%7C%5Cleq+%5C%23%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{|u_{&#92;mathcal{D}}(&#92;alpha)|&#92;leq &#92;#&#92;mathcal{D}}\" class=\"latex\" /> for all <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha%5Cin%5Cmathbb%7BR%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;alpha&#92;in&#92;mathbb{R}}\" class=\"latex\" />):</p>\n<blockquote><p><b>Lemma 2 (Erdös&#8211;Mauduit&#8211;Sárközy)</b> <em>Let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bt%3A%3D%5C%23%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{t:=&#92;#&#92;mathcal{D}}\" class=\"latex\" />. For any <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha%5Cin%5Cmathbb%7BR%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;alpha&#92;in&#92;mathbb{R}}\" class=\"latex\" />, one has</em></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+%7Cu_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%28%5Calpha%29%7C%5Cleq+t%5Cleft%281-%5Cfrac%7B%5C%7C%5Calpha%5C%7C%5E2%7D%7B%28r-1%29%5E5%7D%5Cright%29&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle |u_{&#92;mathcal{D}}(&#92;alpha)|&#92;leq t&#92;left(1-&#92;frac{&#92;|&#92;alpha&#92;|^2}{(r-1)^5}&#92;right)\" class=\"latex\" /></p>\n<p><em>where <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5C%7C%5Calpha%5C%7C%3A%3D%5Cmin%5Climits_%7Bn%5Cin%5Cmathbb%7BZ%7D%7D%7C%5Calpha-n%7C%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;|&#92;alpha&#92;|:=&#92;min&#92;limits_{n&#92;in&#92;mathbb{Z}}|&#92;alpha-n|}\" class=\"latex\" />.</em></p></blockquote>\n<p>In order to take full advantage of the saving on the right-hand side of the inequality, one needs the following lemma:</p>\n<blockquote><p><b>Lemma 3 (Mauduit&#8211;Sárközy)</b> <em>For any <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cbeta%5Cin%5Cmathbb%7BR%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;beta&#92;in&#92;mathbb{R}}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bq%5Cleq+r%5E%7B%28N-8%29%2F2%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{q&#92;leq r^{(N-8)/2}}\" class=\"latex\" />, one has</em></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+%5Csum%5Climits_%7B0%5Cleq+k%3CN%7D%5Cleft%5C%7C%5Cbeta%2B%5Cfrac%7Bhr%5Ek%7D%7Bq%7D%5Cright%5C%7C%5Cgeq+%5Cfrac%7B%28r-1%29%5E2%7D%7B128%7D%5Cfrac%7BN%7D%7B%5Clog+q%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle &#92;sum&#92;limits_{0&#92;leq k<N}&#92;left&#92;|&#92;beta+&#92;frac{hr^k}{q}&#92;right&#92;|&#92;geq &#92;frac{(r-1)^2}{128}&#92;frac{N}{&#92;log q}\" class=\"latex\" /></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The details of the derivation of the desired theorem from the two lemmas above is explained in Section 4 of Erdös&#8211;Mauduit&#8211;Sárközy paper. <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5CBox&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;Box\" class=\"latex\" /></p>\n<p>The methods of Erdös&#8211;Mauduit&#8211;Sárközy above paved the way to further results about ellipsephic integers. For instance, similarly to <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bombieri--Vinogradov_theorem\">Bombieri&#8211;Vinogradov theorem</a>, it is natural to expect that the distribution result of Erdös&#8211;Mauduit&#8211;Sárközy gets better on average: as it turns out, this was done independently by <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=1752255\">C. Dartyge and C. Mauduit</a>, and S. <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=1832701\">Konyagin</a> (circa 2000):</p>\n<blockquote><p><b>Theorem 4 (Dartyge&#8211;Mauduit, Konyagin)</b> <em>There exists <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha%3D%5Calpha%28r%2Ct%29%3E0%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;alpha=&#92;alpha(r,t)>0}\" class=\"latex\" /> such that for all <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BB%3E0%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{B>0}\" class=\"latex\" /> there exists <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BA%3E0%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{A>0}\" class=\"latex\" /> with the property that</em></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+%5Csum%5Climits_%7B%5Csubstack%7Bq%5Cleq+x%5E%7B%5Calpha%7D%2F%28%5Clog+x%29%5EA%2C%5C%5C+%5Ctextrm%7Bgcd%7D%28q%2Cr%28r-1%29%29%3D1%7D%7D%5Cleft%7C%5C%23W_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%28x%2Ca%2Cq%29-%5Cfrac%7B%5C%23W_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%28x%29%7D%7Bq%7D%5Cright%7C%5Cll+%5Cfrac%7B%5C%23W_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%28x%29%7D%7B%28%5Clog+x%29%5EB%7D.&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle &#92;sum&#92;limits_{&#92;substack{q&#92;leq x^{&#92;alpha}/(&#92;log x)^A,&#92;&#92; &#92;textrm{gcd}(q,r(r-1))=1}}&#92;left|&#92;#W_{&#92;mathcal{D}}(x,a,q)-&#92;frac{&#92;#W_{&#92;mathcal{D}}(x)}{q}&#92;right|&#92;ll &#92;frac{&#92;#W_{&#92;mathcal{D}}(x)}{(&#92;log x)^B}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><em>Proof:</em> One uses Lemmas 2 and 3 above, a <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Large_sieve\">large sieve method</a>, and some bounds on the moments</p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+%5Cint_0%5E1+%7CF_%7BN%2C%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%28s%29%7C%5Em+%5C%2C+ds&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle &#92;int_0^1 |F_{N,&#92;mathcal{D}}(s)|^m &#92;, ds\" class=\"latex\" /></p>\n<p>of the function <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BF_%7BN%2C%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{F_{N,&#92;mathcal{D}}}\" class=\"latex\" />. <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5CBox&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;Box\" class=\"latex\" /></p>\n<blockquote><p><b>Remark 1</b> <em>More recently, <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=3620841\">K. Aloui, C. Mauduit and M. Mkaouar</a> improved (in 2017) some of the results of Erdös&#8211;Mauduit&#8211;Sárközy to obtain some distribution results for ellipsephic and <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Palindromic_number\">palindromic</a> integers.</em></p></blockquote>\n<p><b>3. Ellipsephic primes and almost primes</b></p>\n<p>By pursuing sieve methods, <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=1876274\">Dartyge and Mauduit</a> obtained in 2001 the following result about ellipsephic <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Almost_prime\">almost primes</a>:</p>\n<blockquote><p><b>Theorem 5 (Dartyge&#8211;Mauduit)</b> <em>There exists <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%3Dk%28r%2C+t%29%5Cin%5Cmathbb%7BN%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{k=k(r, t)&#92;in&#92;mathbb{N}}\" class=\"latex\" /> such that</em></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+%5C%23%5C%7Bn%5Cin+W_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%28x%29%3A+%5COmega%28n%29%5Cleq+k%5C%7D%5Cgg%5Cfrac%7B%5C%23W_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%28x%29%7D%7B%5Clog+x%7D%2C&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle &#92;#&#92;{n&#92;in W_{&#92;mathcal{D}}(x): &#92;Omega(n)&#92;leq k&#92;}&#92;gg&#92;frac{&#92;#W_{&#92;mathcal{D}}(x)}{&#92;log x},\" class=\"latex\" /></p>\n<p><em>where <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5COmega%28n%29%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;Omega(n)}\" class=\"latex\" /> stands for the number of prime factors of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{n}\" class=\"latex\" /> (counted with multiplicity).</em></p></blockquote>\n<p>A natural question motivated by this theorem concerns the determination of explicit values of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{k}\" class=\"latex\" /> in the previous statement. The answer to this question is somewhat related to the value of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;alpha}\" class=\"latex\" /> in the last theorem of the previous section and, in this direction, it is possible to show that</p>\n<ul>\n<li>if <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%3D%5C%7B0%2C1%5C%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;mathcal{D}=&#92;{0,1&#92;}}\" class=\"latex\" />, then one can take\n<ul>\n<li><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%3D3%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{k=3}\" class=\"latex\" /> (and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha%5Csim1%2F3%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;alpha&#92;sim1/3}\" class=\"latex\" />) for <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Br%3D3%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{r=3}\" class=\"latex\" />,</li>\n<li><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%3D5%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{k=5}\" class=\"latex\" /> (and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha%5Csim+1%2F4%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;alpha&#92;sim 1/4}\" class=\"latex\" />) for <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Br%3D4%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{r=4}\" class=\"latex\" />, &#8230;,</li>\n<li><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%3D23%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{k=23}\" class=\"latex\" /> for <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Br%3D10%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{r=10}\" class=\"latex\" />, and</li>\n<li><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%3D%5Cfrac%7B8%7D%7B%5Cpi%7D%281%2Bo%281%29%29r%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{k=&#92;frac{8}{&#92;pi}(1+o(1))r}\" class=\"latex\" /> as <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Br%5Crightarrow%5Cinfty%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{r&#92;rightarrow&#92;infty}\" class=\"latex\" /></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>if <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%3D%5C%7B0%2C%5Cdots%2Cr-2%5C%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;mathcal{D}=&#92;{0,&#92;dots,r-2&#92;}}\" class=\"latex\" />, <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Br%5Cgeq+5%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{r&#92;geq 5}\" class=\"latex\" />, then one can take <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%3D2%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{k=2}\" class=\"latex\" />.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>In 2009 and 2010, C. Mauduit and J. Rivat proved two conjectures of Gelfond on sums of digits of <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=2680394\">primes</a> and <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=2545827\">squares</a>. The methods in these articles gave hope to reach the case <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%3D1%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{k=1}\" class=\"latex\" /> (of ellipsephic primes) in Dartyge&#8211;Mauduit theorem above. This was recently accomplished by <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=3958793\">J. Maynard</a> in 2016: if <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%3D%5C%7B0%2C%5Cdots%2Cr-1%5C%7D%5Csetminus%5C%7Ba_0%5C%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;mathcal{D}=&#92;{0,&#92;dots,r-1&#92;}&#92;setminus&#92;{a_0&#92;}}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Br%5Cgeq+10%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{r&#92;geq 10}\" class=\"latex\" />, then</p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+%5C%23%5C%7Bp%5Cin+W_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%28x%29%3A+p+%5Ctextrm%7B+prime%7D%5C%7D%5Cgg+%5Cfrac%7B%5C%23W_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%28x%29%7D%7B%5Clog+x%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle &#92;#&#92;{p&#92;in W_{&#92;mathcal{D}}(x): p &#92;textrm{ prime}&#92;}&#92;gg &#92;frac{&#92;#W_{&#92;mathcal{D}}(x)}{&#92;log x}\" class=\"latex\" /></p>\n<blockquote><p><b>Remark 2</b> <em>In his <a href=\"https://ora.ox.ac.uk/objects/uuid:40f5511c-af6b-4215-b1ab-97f203e8936b\">thesis</a>, A. Irving got analogous results for palindromic ellipsephic integers with <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B3%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{3}\" class=\"latex\" /> digits in basis <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Br%5Cgeq+4%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{r&#92;geq 4}\" class=\"latex\" /> with two prime factors.</em></p></blockquote>\n<p>After this brief discussion of ellipsephic almost primes, let us now talk about ellipsephic integers possessing only small prime factors.</p>\n<p><b>4. Friable ellipsephic integers</b></p>\n<p>Recall that a <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smooth_number\">friable integer</a> is an integer without large prime factors. For later reference, we denote the largest prime factor of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{n}\" class=\"latex\" /> by</p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+p%5E%2B%28n%29%3A%3D%5Cmax%5Climits_%7B%5Csubstack%7Bp%7Cn%5C%5Cp%5Ctextrm%7B+prime%7D%7D%7D+p.&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle p^+(n):=&#92;max&#92;limits_{&#92;substack{p|n&#92;&#92;p&#92;textrm{ prime}}} p.\" class=\"latex\" /></p>\n<p>It was shown by <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=1692287\">Erdös&#8211;Mauduit&#8211;Sárközy</a> that, for any fixed <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Ba%5Cin%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%5Csetminus%5C%7B0%5C%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{a&#92;in&#92;mathcal{D}&#92;setminus&#92;{0&#92;}}\" class=\"latex\" /> and for all <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cvarepsilon%3E0%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;varepsilon>0}\" class=\"latex\" />, there are <em>infinitely many</em> ellipsephic integers <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn%5Cin+W_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{n&#92;in W_{&#92;mathcal{D}}}\" class=\"latex\" /> of the form <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bn%3D%5Csum%5Climits_%7Bi%3D0%7D%5E%7Bk-1%7Dar%5Ei%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{n=&#92;sum&#92;limits_{i=0}^{k-1}ar^i}\" class=\"latex\" /> whose largest prime factor is <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp%5E%2B%28n%29%5Cleq+n%5E%7B%5Cvarepsilon%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{p^+(n)&#92;leq n^{&#92;varepsilon}}\" class=\"latex\" />.</p>\n<p>Logically, this results motivates the question to establish the existence of a <em>positive proportion</em> of friable ellipsephic integers. This seems a hard task for <em>arbitrary</em> <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cvarepsilon%3E0%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;varepsilon>0}\" class=\"latex\" />, but this problem becomes more tractable for small values of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cvarepsilon%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;varepsilon}\" class=\"latex\" /> when the basis <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Br%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{r}\" class=\"latex\" /> is large enough.</p>\n<p>In fact, <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=2487242\">S. Col</a> showed that there exists <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B0%3C%5Calpha%3D%5Calpha%28r%2C%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%29%3C1%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{0<&#92;alpha=&#92;alpha(r,&#92;mathcal{D})<1}\" class=\"latex\" /> such that</p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+%5C%23%5C%7Bn%5Cin+W_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%28x%29%3A+p%5E%2B%28n%29%3Cn%5E%7B%5Calpha%7D%5C%7D%5Cgg%5C%23W_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%28x%29.&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle &#92;#&#92;{n&#92;in W_{&#92;mathcal{D}}(x): p^+(n)<n^{&#92;alpha}&#92;}&#92;gg&#92;#W_{&#92;mathcal{D}}(x).\" class=\"latex\" /></p>\n<p>Moreover, if <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%3D%5C%7B0%2C1%5C%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;mathcal{D}=&#92;{0,1&#92;}}\" class=\"latex\" />, then it is possible to take <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha%3D1-%5Cfrac%7B%5Cpi%7D%7B4r%7D%5Cleft%281-%5Cfrac%7B3%5Cpi%7D%7B4r%7D%5Cright%29%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;alpha=1-&#92;frac{&#92;pi}{4r}&#92;left(1-&#92;frac{3&#92;pi}{4r}&#92;right)}\" class=\"latex\" /> (which is close to one for <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Br%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{r}\" class=\"latex\" /> large). On the other hand, <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Calpha%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;alpha}\" class=\"latex\" /> can be taken very small when <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%3D%5C%7B0%2C%5Cdots%2Cr-1%5C%7D%5Csetminus%5C%7Ba_0%5C%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;mathcal{D}=&#92;{0,&#92;dots,r-1&#92;}&#92;setminus&#92;{a_0&#92;}}\" class=\"latex\" /> and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Br%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{r}\" class=\"latex\" /> sufficiently large.</p>\n<p><b>5. Ellipsephic solutions to Vinogradov systems</b></p>\n<p>A <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vinogradov's_mean-value_theorem\">Vinogradov system</a> is a system of equations on the variables <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx_1%2C%5Cdots%2C+x_s%2C+y_1%2C+%5Cdots%2C+y_s%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{x_1,&#92;dots, x_s, y_1, &#92;dots, y_s}\" class=\"latex\" /> of the form:</p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+x_1%5Ej%2B%5Cdots%2Bx_s%5Ej+%3D+y_1%5Ej%2B%5Cdots%2By_s%5Ej%2C+%5Cquad+1%5Cleq+j%5Cleq+k.&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle x_1^j+&#92;dots+x_s^j = y_1^j+&#92;dots+y_s^j, &#92;quad 1&#92;leq j&#92;leq k.\" class=\"latex\" /></p>\n<p>A major breakthrough on counting solutions to Vinogradov systems was famously obtained by <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=3548534\">J. Bourgain, C. Demeter and L. Guth</a> (see also the <a href=\"http://www.bourbaki.ens.fr/TEXTES/1134.pdf\">text</a> and the <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=u2b64UbYHyc\">video</a> of L. Pierce&#8217;s Bourbaki seminar talk on this subject).</p>\n<p>Concerning ellipsephic solutions to Vinogradov systems (i.e., solutions with <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx_i%2C+y_i%5Cin+W_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{x_i, y_i&#92;in W_{&#92;mathcal{D}}}\" class=\"latex\" /> for all <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B1%5Cleq+i%5Cleq+s%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{1&#92;leq i&#92;leq s}\" class=\"latex\" />), Kirsty Briggs showed that for <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bk%3D2%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{k=2}\" class=\"latex\" />, <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Br%3Dp%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{r=p}\" class=\"latex\" /> prime and <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%3D%5C%7Bd%5E2%3A+d%3C%5Csqrt%7Bp%7D%5C%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;mathcal{D}=&#92;{d^2: d<&#92;sqrt{p}&#92;}}\" class=\"latex\" />, the trivial bound <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cleq+%5C%23W_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%28x%29%5E%7B2s%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;leq &#92;#W_{&#92;mathcal{D}}(x)^{2s}}\" class=\"latex\" /> on the number of solutions of the Vinogradov system</p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+x_1%2B%5Cdots%2B+x_s%3Dy_1%2B%5Cdots%2By_s%2C&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle x_1+&#92;dots+ x_s=y_1+&#92;dots+y_s,\" class=\"latex\" /></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+x_1%5E2%2B%5Cdots%2Bx_s%5E2%3Dy_1%5E2%2B%5Cdots%2By_s%5E2&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle x_1^2+&#92;dots+x_s^2=y_1^2+&#92;dots+y_s^2\" class=\"latex\" /></p>\n<p>with <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx_i%2C+y_i%5Cin+W_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%28x%29%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{x_i, y_i&#92;in W_{&#92;mathcal{D}}(x)}\" class=\"latex\" /> can be improved into <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cll_%7B%5Cvarepsilon%7D+%5C%23W_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%28x%29%5E%7B2s-6%2B%5Cvarepsilon%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;ll_{&#92;varepsilon} &#92;#W_{&#92;mathcal{D}}(x)^{2s-6+&#92;varepsilon}}\" class=\"latex\" /> <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cforall+%5C%2C%5Cvarepsilon%3E0%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;forall &#92;,&#92;varepsilon>0}\" class=\"latex\" /> whenever <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bs%5Cgeq+6%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{s&#92;geq 6}\" class=\"latex\" />. (In particular, this result is saying that in the case <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bs%3D6%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{s=6}\" class=\"latex\" />, the main contribution to the number of ellipsephic solutions of the corresponding Vinogradov system comes from the trivial solutions <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx_i%3Dy_i%5Cin+W_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%28x%29%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{x_i=y_i&#92;in W_{&#92;mathcal{D}}(x)}\" class=\"latex\" />.)</p>\n<p><b>6. Ellipsephic numbers in finite fields</b></p>\n<p>The notion of finite-field analogs of ellipsephic numbers was studied by several authors including <a href=\"https://mathscinet.ams.org/mathscinet-getitem?mr=3326124\">Dartyge, Mauduit and Sárközy</a>.</p>\n<p>In order to explain some results in this direction, let us setup some notations. Let <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bq%3Dp%5Er%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{q=p^r}\" class=\"latex\" /> be the power of a prime number <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bp%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{p}\" class=\"latex\" /> and denote by <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bz%5Cin+%5Cmathbb%7BF%7D_q%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{z&#92;in &#92;mathbb{F}_q}\" class=\"latex\" /> a <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Primitive_element_theorem\">primitive element</a> generating a basis <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathcal%7BB%7D%3D%5C%7B1%2Cz%2C%5Cdots%2C+z%5E%7Br-1%7D%5C%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;mathcal{B}=&#92;{1,z,&#92;dots, z^{r-1}&#92;}}\" class=\"latex\" /> of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathbb%7BF%7D_q%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;mathbb{F}_q}\" class=\"latex\" /> over <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathbb%7BF%7D_p%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;mathbb{F}_p}\" class=\"latex\" />. In this way, we can represent a number <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bx%5Cin%5Cmathbb%7BF%7D_q%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{x&#92;in&#92;mathbb{F}_q}\" class=\"latex\" /> as</p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+x%3D%5Csum%5Climits_%7Bi%3D0%7D%5E%7Br-1%7D+c_i+z%5Ei+%5Cquad+%5Ctextrm%7B+with+%7D0%5Cleq+c_i%3Cp.&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle x=&#92;sum&#92;limits_{i=0}^{r-1} c_i z^i &#92;quad &#92;textrm{ with }0&#92;leq c_i<p.\" class=\"latex\" /></p>\n<p>Given a set of digits <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%5Csubset%5C%7B0%2C%5Cdots%2C+p-1%5C%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;mathcal{D}&#92;subset&#92;{0,&#92;dots, p-1&#92;}}\" class=\"latex\" /> with <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B2%5Cleq+%5C%23%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%5Cleq+p-1%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{2&#92;leq &#92;#&#92;mathcal{D}&#92;leq p-1}\" class=\"latex\" />, the associated subset of ellipsephic numbers is</p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+W_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%3A%3D%5Cleft%5C%7B%5Csum%5Climits_%7Bi%3D0%7D%5E%7Br-1%7D+c_iz%5Ei%3A+c_i%5Cin%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D+%5C%2C%5C%2C%5C%2C%5Cforall%5C%2C+0%5Cleq+i%5Cleq+r-1%5Cright%5C%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle W_{&#92;mathcal{D}}:=&#92;left&#92;{&#92;sum&#92;limits_{i=0}^{r-1} c_iz^i: c_i&#92;in&#92;mathcal{D} &#92;,&#92;,&#92;,&#92;forall&#92;, 0&#92;leq i&#92;leq r-1&#92;right&#92;}\" class=\"latex\" /></p>\n<p>Given a polynomial <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%28x%29%5Cin%5Cmathbb%7BF%7D_q%5Bx%5D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{f(x)&#92;in&#92;mathbb{F}_q[x]}\" class=\"latex\" />, we can study the set of its ellipsephic values via the set</p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+W_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%28f%29%3A%3D%5C%7Ba%5Cin%5Cmathbb%7BF%7D_q%3A+f%28a%29%5Cin+W_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%5C%7D.&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle W_{&#92;mathcal{D}}(f):=&#92;{a&#92;in&#92;mathbb{F}_q: f(a)&#92;in W_{&#92;mathcal{D}}&#92;}.\" class=\"latex\" /></p>\n<p>The size of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7BW_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%28f%29%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{W_{&#92;mathcal{D}}(f)}\" class=\"latex\" /> is described by the following theorem:</p>\n<blockquote><p><b>Theorem 6 (Dartyge&#8211;Mauduit&#8211;Sárközy)</b> <em>If <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Ctextrm%7Bdeg%7D%28f%29%3Dn%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;textrm{deg}(f)=n}\" class=\"latex\" />, then</em></p>\n<p align=\"center\"><img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%5Cdisplaystyle+%5Cleft%7C%5C%23W_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%28f%29-%5C%23W_%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%5Cright%7C%5Cleq+%5Cfrac%7Bn-1%7D%7B%5Csqrt%7Bq%7D%7D%5Cleft%28%5C%23%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%2Bp%5Csqrt%7Bp-%5C%23%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D%5Cright%29&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"&#92;displaystyle &#92;left|&#92;#W_{&#92;mathcal{D}}(f)-&#92;#W_{&#92;mathcal{D}}&#92;right|&#92;leq &#92;frac{n-1}{&#92;sqrt{q}}&#92;left(&#92;#&#92;mathcal{D}+p&#92;sqrt{p-&#92;#&#92;mathcal{D}}&#92;right)\" class=\"latex\" /></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>This result is specially interesting when <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;mathcal{D}}\" class=\"latex\" /> contains a positive proportion of <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathbb%7BF%7D_p%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;mathbb{F}_p}\" class=\"latex\" />. Moreover, it can be improved when <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7B%5Cmathcal%7BD%7D%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{&#92;mathcal{D}}\" class=\"latex\" /> contains consecutive digits.</p>\n<p>More recently, a better result was obtained by <a href=\"https://mathscinet-ams-org.ezproxy.math.cnrs.fr/mathscinet-getitem?mr=3710628\">R. Dietmann, C. Elsholtz and I. Shparlinski</a> for the case <img src=\"https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=%7Bf%28x%29%3Dx%5E2%7D&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002\" alt=\"{f(x)=x^2}\" class=\"latex\" />. Finally, the reader can consult the <a href=\"https://mathscinet-ams-org.ezproxy.math.cnrs.fr/mathscinet-getitem?mr=3788642\">work of C. Swaenepoel</a> for further results.</p>\n",
  "wfw:commentRss": "https://matheuscmss.wordpress.com/2019/12/22/dartyges-talk-on-ellipsephic-integers/feed/",
